**What is Inheritance?** Allows a class to inherit attributes and methods from another class. Python supports Single, Multiple, Multilevel, and Hierarchical inheritance.

<pre class='bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-800 font-mono'>class Animal:
    def eat(self): print("Eating")

class Dog(Animal):
    def bark(self): print("Woof!")

my_dog = Dog()
my_dog.eat()   # Inherited</pre>

**Method Resolution Order (MRO):** `print(ClassName.__mro__)` shows the lookup order for methods in multiple inheritance.

**What is a Class?** A blueprint or template for creating objects. It defines properties (fields) and behaviors (methods).
**What is an Object?** An instance of a class – a concrete entity created from the blueprint.

<pre class='bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-800 font-mono'>public class Car {
    String brand;
    String color;
    int speed;

    public Car(String brand, String color) {
        this.brand = brand;
        this.color = color;
        this.speed = 0;
    }

    public void accelerate() {
        speed += 10;
        System.out.println(brand + " is going " + speed + " km/h");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Car myCar = new Car("Toyota", "Red");
        myCar.accelerate();
    }
}</pre>

**Key Points:**
• Use `class` keyword.
• Use `new` keyword to create objects.
• `this` refers to current object.
• Constructor has same name as class.

**What is Encapsulation?** Bundling data (fields) and methods within a class, and restricting direct access to some components.

**Access Modifiers:**
• `private`: Only accessible within the class
• `protected`: Accessible within package and subclasses
• `public`: Accessible from anywhere
• `default`: Accessible within the same package

<pre class='bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-800 font-mono'>public class BankAccount {
    private double balance;

    public BankAccount(double initialBalance) {
        this.balance = initialBalance;
    }

    public double getBalance() { return balance; }

    public void deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0) balance += amount;
    }
}</pre>

**Benefits:** Data hiding, controlled access, and validation before modification.

**What is Inheritance?** Allows a child class (subclass) to inherit properties and methods from a parent class (superclass).

**Types in Java:** Single, Multilevel, Hierarchical. (Note: Java doesn't support multiple inheritance with classes - use interfaces).

<pre class='bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-800 font-mono'>public class Animal {
    protected String name;
    public Animal(String name) { this.name = name; }
    public void eat() { System.out.println("Eating"); }
}

public class Dog extends Animal {
    public Dog(String name) { super(name); }
    @Override
    public void eat() { System.out.println(name + " eating dog food"); }
}</pre>

**Key Points:** Use `extends` keyword. `super` refers to parent class. Use `@Override` annotation for overridden methods. Child class inherits all non-private members.

**What is Polymorphism?** "Many forms". Allows objects to be treated as instances of their parent class while behaving according to their actual class.

**Compile-time (Static): Method Overloading**
Same method name, different parameters.
<pre class='bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-800 font-mono'>public int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
public double add(double a, double b) { return a + b; }</pre>

**Runtime (Dynamic): Method Overriding**
<pre class='bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-800 font-mono'>Shape[] shapes = { new Circle(5), new Rectangle(4, 6) };
for (Shape shape : shapes) {
    shape.draw();  // Calls appropriate overridden method
}</pre>

**What is Abstraction?** Hiding complex implementation details and showing only essential features.

**Abstract Classes vs Interfaces:**
<pre class='bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-800 font-mono'>// Abstract class - cannot instantiate directly
public abstract class Vehicle {
    public abstract void start(); // Must be implemented by child
    public void display() { }      // Concrete method allowed
}

// Interface - 100% Abstraction
public interface Flyable {
    void fly(); // implicitly public abstract
}</pre>

**Abstract Class vs Interface:**
• **Methods:** Abstract classes can have both abstract and concrete. Interfaces all abstract (Java 8+ can have default methods).
• **Variables:** Abstract classes can have instance variables. Interfaces only have constants (`public static final`).
• **Inheritance:** Single inheritance for classes vs Multiple interfaces.
• **Constructor:** Classes have them, interfaces don't.

**What is a Class?** A user-defined data type containing data members and member functions.
**What is an Object?** An instance of a class.

<pre class='bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-800 font-mono'>#include &lt;iostream&gt;
using namespace std;

class Car {
private:
    string brand;
    int speed;

public:
    Car(string b) {
        brand = b;
        speed = 0;
    }

    void accelerate() {
        speed += 10;
        cout &lt;&lt; brand &lt;&lt; " is now going " &lt;&lt; speed &lt;&lt; " km/h\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Car myCar("Toyota");
    myCar.accelerate();
    return 0;
}</pre>

**Key Points:**
• Access specifiers: `public`, `private`, `protected`.
• Constructor has same name as class.
• Use dot operator (`.`) to access members.

**What is Encapsulation?** Bundling data and methods together while restricting direct access to internal data.

**Access Specifiers:**
• `private`: Only accessible within the class
• `protected`: Accessible in class and derived classes
• `public`: Accessible from anywhere

<pre class='bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-800 font-mono'>class BankAccount {
private:
    double balance;
public:
    BankAccount(double initial) : balance(initial) {}

    // const indicates it doesn't modify the object
    double getBalance() const { return balance; }

    void deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0) balance += amount;
    }
};</pre>

**What is Inheritance?** Allows a class to inherit properties and methods from another class. C++ supports Multiple Inheritance!

<pre class='bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-800 font-mono'>class Animal {
protected:
    string name;
public:
    Animal(string n) : name(n) {}
    void eat() { cout &lt;&lt; "Eating\n"; }
};

class Dog : public Animal {
public:
    Dog(string n) : Animal(n) {} // Call base constructor
    void eat() { cout &lt;&lt; name &lt;&lt; " eating dog food\n"; }
};</pre>

**Multiple Inheritance Example:** `class Duck : public Flyable, public Swimmable { ... };`

**Compile-time Polymorphism (Overloading):** Multiple functions with the same name but different parameters.

**Runtime Polymorphism (Virtual Functions):**
<pre class='bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-800 font-mono'>class Shape {
public:
    virtual void draw() { cout &lt;&lt; "Drawing shape\n"; }
    virtual ~Shape() {} // Virtual destructor is essential!
};

class Circle : public Shape {
public:
    void draw() override { cout &lt;&lt; "Drawing circle\n"; }
};

int main() {
    Shape* shape = new Circle();
    shape-&gt;draw(); // Calls Circle's draw
    delete shape;
}</pre>

**Key Points:** `virtual` in base class, `override` in derived class. Without `virtual`, early binding calls the base method.

**Abstract Classes:** A class with at least one pure virtual function (`= 0`). Cannot be instantiated.

<pre class='bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-800 font-mono'>class Vehicle {
public:
    virtual void start() = 0; // Pure virtual function
    virtual ~Vehicle() {}
};</pre>

**Interface (Pure Abstract Class):** C++ has no native `interface` keyword, but an abstract class with *only* pure virtual functions serves as an interface.

**Abstract vs Interface in C++:**
• **Abstract Class:** Can have concrete methods and data members. Partial implementation.
• **Interface:** All pure virtual methods, usually no data. Defines a strict contract.

**Templates** allow you to write generic code that works with any data type.

**Function Templates:**
<pre class='bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-800 font-mono'>template &lt;typename T&gt;
T maximum(T a, T b) {
    return (a > b) ? a : b;
}
cout &lt;&lt; maximum(10, 20); // int
cout &lt;&lt; maximum(3.14, 2.71); // double</pre>

**Class Templates:**
<pre class='bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-800 font-mono'>template &lt;typename K, typename V&gt;
class Pair {
private:
    K key;
    V value;
public:
    Pair(K k, V v) : key(k), value(v) {}
};
Pair&lt;string, int&gt; age("Alice", 25);</pre>
